entry.title: gpu: Fix potential CurrentGL dangling pointer
entry.content:
There's a potential issue with GLContextEGL::ReleaseBackpressureFences

leaving the thread local CurrentGL pointer set if there was no previous

current context. This means that the pointer will be dangling when the

context is destroyed. This ordinarily doesn't happen with Ganesh/GL

since there's almost always a current GL context, but it's possible with

Graphite when SharedContext won't ever make its context current.



This CL also cleans up the code related to setting the thread local

CurrentGL pointer:



- GetGlContextForCurrentThread returns a reference to the thread local

CurrentGL pointer so it's renamed to ThreadLocalCurrentGL and is

not exposed via gl_bindings.h (see below).

- GetThreadLocalCurrentGL returns the CurrentGL pointer and is exported

in gl_bindings.h. It does not return a mutable reference though.

- SetCurrentGL sets the thread local CurrentGL pointer so it's renamed

to SetThreadLocalCurrentGL to distinguish it from GetCurrentGL which

is an accessor on the GLContext class.

entry.title: Re-land: CHECK that style and layout are not left dirty during lifecycle
entry.content:
The first iteration of this patch, https://crrev.com/1192759, was

reverted due to scroll animations leaving style and layout dirty

(https://crbug.com/1478009). This turns out to be working as intended

so this patch moves the cleanliness check below

`RunScrollSnapshotClientSteps`.



Original change description below:

`LocalFrameView::UpdateLifecyclePhasesInternal` is responsible for

running the lifecycle and uses the following high-level pattern:

while (true) {

RunStyleAndLayoutLifecyclePhases();



bool needs_to_repeat_lifecycle = RunStepA();

if (needs_to_repeat_lifecycle) { continue; }



bool needs_to_repeat_lifecycle = RunStepB();

if (needs_to_repeat_lifecycle) { continue; }

...

}

Each step expects clean style and layout, and if a step dirties style

or layout, it should re-start the lifecycle. This patch adds CHECKs for

many of the lifecycle steps which ensures style and layout are not left

dirty. These checks are added inside functions when possible, to

provide more helpful crash stacks.

entry.title: [SBv5] Migrate SBv5 proto from alpha to GA
entry.content:
This migration requires the following changes in Chrome:

1) Rename safebrowsingv5_alpha1.proto to safebrowsingv5.proto

2) Remove the `filter` in SearchHashesRequest. Remove SUSPICIOUS and

SOCIAL_ENGINEERING_ADS from ThreatType.

3) Change the SearchHashes endpoint to https://safebrowsing.googleapis.com/v5/hashes:search.

4) Because of the removal of SUSPICIOUS threat type, we need to map

SOCIAL_ENGINEERING + CANARY back to SB_THREAT_TYPE_SUSPICIOUS_SITE.

This change is reflected in the MapFullHashDetailToSbThreatType

function.



Currently the backend will only set CANARY for

ABUSIVE_EXPERIENCE_VIOLATION, BETTER_ADS_VIOLATION, API_ABUSE and

SOCIAL_ENGINEERING (only SOCIAL_ENGINEERING is relevant to this CL

since others are not frame URLs. Chrome should discard the whole

FullHashDetail if CANARY is seen with other threat type (e.g. MALWARE).



If CANARY and FRAME_ONLY are both presented in one single

FullHashDetail, Chrome should discard it.



This change will not be gated by a separate flag. Going forward, HPRT

for SSB (SafeBrowsingHashPrefixRealTimeLookups) and the experiment on

ESB users (SafeBrowsingLookupMechanismExperiment) will be reaching the

GA endpoint.

entry.title: [flex] Mitigate performance drop during dynamic flex change.
entry.content:
I haven't got a good reproducible test yet, but the issue experienced

in 1479477 is related to a dynamic size change.



There are two layouts which can occur during flexbox column wrap

intrinsic sizing.

border/padding if the child is layout clean.
